prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Our 19 sources are well within 10 degrees on the sky and so share a common calabrator. We do not expect any extended emission towards these sources and so do not require the ACA. The provided line widths are typical for a 50 AU disk inclined at 60 degrees, which is the average inclination angle assuming a sample with random orientations.
Requested Sensitivity To estimated the anticipated level of line emission we used the non-LTE line modeler LIME to sumulate emission from a 0.04 solar mass disk with an inclination of 60 degrees and a radial extent of 50 AU, the minimum radius for which we wish to detect emission. The request angular resolution of 0.59 arcseconds for 12CO and 0.62 arcseconds for 13CO will allow us to resolve a 50 AU disk at 135 parsecs. Running this model through the ALMA simulator gave a peak line flux of 0.2 Jy/beam for 12CO 3-2 and a peak flux of 0.13 Jy/beam for 13CO 3-2(see Figure 3 in the Science Justification). Therefore a 20 sigma detection will require a sensitivity of 10 mJy per beam. This requires 2.67 hours of observing time for the 12CO line and 3.06 for the 13CO line for a total time of 5.73 hours.
Correlator setup The primary target line in our first science goal is the 12CO 3-2 line at 345.795 GHz. The LO has been shifted slightly to include two potentially weak but detectable lines, H13CN 4-3 and H13CO+ 4-3. Both of these lines trace high density regions and will add to the legacy value of this program. In addition, we set one of the basebands to be optimized for continuum at 335 GHz.
For our second science goal the primary target line is 13CO 3-2 at 330.588 GHz. The LO has been shifted to include the C18O 3-2 line, which we will use in conjunction with the 13CO line to obtain disk gas masses. One baseband has been optimized for continuum at 318 GHz.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: To date most molecular studies of protoplanetary disks have focused on large, isolated disks. However most disks are less massive and form in clusters where they are subject to an elevated external radiation field, and are thus likely to be more compact and less massive. The Sun likely formed in such conditions. We propose to detect 12CO and 13CO toward 19 low mass disks in the rho Ophiuchi star forming region. These disks are near two massive B stars, which significantly enhance the local interstellar radiation field. These observations will allow us to determine the importance of such enhanced fields in shaping the physical properties of the disks (size and therefore mass, thermal balance) as well as providing a legacy data set for indepth studies of typical molecular disks.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Circumstellar disks, exoplanets and the solar system
